===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|perseveren}}, from {{der|en|fro|perseverer}}, from {{der|en|la|persevērō|persevērāre|t=to continue steadfastly, persist, persevere}}, from {{m|la|perseverus|t=very strict or earnest}}, from {{m|la|per|t=through, by the means of}} + {{m|la|severus|t=strict, earnest}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{rhymes|en|ɪə(ɹ)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[persist]] steadfastly in pursuit of an [[undertaking]], [[task]], [[journey]], or [[goal]], even if [[hinder]]ed by [[distraction]], [[difficulty]], [[obstacle]]s, or [[discouragement]].
#* '''1606''', [[w:William Shakespeare|William Shakespeare]], ''King Lear'', act 3, scene 5:
#*: I will '''persevere''' in
#*: my course of loyalty, though the conflict be sore
#*: between that and my blood.
#* '''1817''', [[w:Jane Austen|Jane Austen]], ''Persuasion'', ch. 1:
#*: Sir Walter had sought the acquaintance, and though his overtures had not been met with any warmth, he had '''persevered''' in seeking it.
#* {{circa|1918}} [[w:P. G. Wodehouse|P. G. Wodehouse]], "The Agonies of Writing a Musical Comedy":
#*: He is a trifle discouraged, but he '''perseveres'''.
# {{lb|en|intransitive|copulative|obsolete}} To stay [[constant]]; to [[continue]] in a certain state; to [[remain]].

